WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.560
 Our next topic is to talk about login and logout.

00:00:02.560 --> 00:00:05.800
 Now just in general, I have this GitHub repository

00:00:05.800 --> 00:00:08.140
 called DJFreeSamples, and every once in a while

00:00:08.140 --> 00:00:11.600
 you ought to see if I've found some bugs and fixed them,

00:00:11.600 --> 00:00:13.660
 so go over to your samples and do a git pull.

00:00:13.660 --> 00:00:16.600
 So every once in a while, just do that.

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:19.260
 So Django, like in lots of situations,

00:00:19.260 --> 00:00:22.680
 comes with a built-in login/logout system.

00:00:22.680 --> 00:00:26.640
 There's lots of ways to do it, you can read up on it,

00:00:26.640 --> 00:00:29.580
 it has a way to create users, has this nice admin interface,

00:00:29.580 --> 00:00:31.220
 and so one of the things we like about Django

00:00:31.220 --> 00:00:32.220
 is that we don't have to build

00:00:32.220 --> 00:00:35.140
 some of these basic maintenance things.

00:00:35.140 --> 00:00:36.800
 It has permissions and groups,

00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:39.200
 we use this in the local library application,

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:42.420
 but we're not gonna use that so much in our applications,

00:00:42.420 --> 00:00:45.320
 and passwords, et cetera, and it has a way

00:00:45.320 --> 00:00:48.600
 to store these things in various techniques.

00:00:48.600 --> 00:00:51.640
 And so the first thing that you'll probably encounter

00:00:51.640 --> 00:00:54.180
 when you're doing this is to create a super user,

00:00:54.180 --> 00:00:56.120
 and so you have to log into your system,

00:00:56.120 --> 00:00:59.220
 you create a super user, give it a name, an email address,

00:00:59.220 --> 00:01:01.900
 the email address is for password recovery,

00:01:01.900 --> 00:01:03.680
 even though you can log in and you can change

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:07.840
 your super user password anywhere, and then you do it.

00:01:07.840 --> 00:01:14.020
 Now there's a great XKCD cartoon for so many things,

00:01:14.020 --> 00:01:17.180
 this is one guy says, "Make me a sandwich,"

00:01:17.180 --> 00:01:19.560
 and the other one says, "What, make it yourself,"

00:01:19.560 --> 00:01:22.720
 and then says, "S-U-D-O, make me a sandwich,"

00:01:22.720 --> 00:01:23.920
 and the other person says, "Okay."

00:01:23.920 --> 00:01:26.460
 So what S-U-D-O means is it's a Linux command

00:01:26.460 --> 00:01:28.920
 to switch to the super user and do a command,

00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:31.580
 so if you don't have permissions to do a command,

00:01:31.580 --> 00:01:35.500
 you can say sudo a command, and so that's what this XKCD,

00:01:35.500 --> 00:01:36.940
 so that's what we call super user,

00:01:36.940 --> 00:01:39.500
 that's the user that has all permissions,

00:01:39.500 --> 00:01:43.580
 doesn't need to get any special permissions.

00:01:43.580 --> 00:01:46.240
 This might be a good time to review what you're going to do

00:01:46.240 --> 00:01:47.420
 when you wipe out your database,

00:01:47.420 --> 00:01:50.280
 when you create that super user, it just adds a row

00:01:50.280 --> 00:01:53.200
 into a table in your DBSQL light,

00:01:53.200 --> 00:01:56.280
 and you can wipe this out any time,

00:01:56.280 --> 00:01:58.880
 that's why I like using SQLite for development

00:01:58.880 --> 00:02:03.440
 in Django, if you remove it, you've removed all the tables,

00:02:03.440 --> 00:02:06.820
 all of the tables created by migrations,

00:02:06.820 --> 00:02:08.800
 the migrate command is what creates tables,

00:02:08.800 --> 00:02:11.040
 the make migration actually creates migrations,

00:02:11.040 --> 00:02:12.240
 what's your Python code.

00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:14.420
 So if you're going to start fresh,

00:02:14.420 --> 00:02:17.820
 you got to remove the DBSQLite file,

00:02:17.820 --> 00:02:20.340
 that's got rid of all your users, all your super users,

00:02:20.340 --> 00:02:22.540
 any data you've put in, it's gone,

00:02:22.540 --> 00:02:24.420
 and then you have to wake it back up

00:02:24.420 --> 00:02:27.460
 with a bunch of empty tables with the manage.py migrate,

00:02:27.460 --> 00:02:29.480
 and you'll see all those things,

00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:33.080
 lots of lines come out at that point, I didn't include them,

00:02:33.080 --> 00:02:34.720
 and then you're going to have to create

00:02:34.720 --> 00:02:35.720
 your super users again.

00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:38.020
 So just if you wipe your database,

00:02:38.020 --> 00:02:40.740
 you got to recreate your super users.

00:02:40.740 --> 00:02:42.980
 Once you have a super user, the rest of the users

00:02:42.980 --> 00:02:45.020
 are put in using the admin interface,

00:02:45.020 --> 00:02:47.800
 you just go in, and among all the other models

00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:49.340
 that you might have in your application,

00:02:49.340 --> 00:02:51.140
 the groups and the users are just models,

00:02:51.140 --> 00:02:53.800
 they're models that happen to be built into Django,

00:02:53.800 --> 00:02:56.540
 and you don't have any responsibility for building them.

00:02:56.540 --> 00:03:00.740
 And so, like I said, the groups and permissions is useful,

00:03:00.740 --> 00:03:01.820
 and you can read up on that,

00:03:01.820 --> 00:03:04.480
 and maybe your application needs to use those,

00:03:04.480 --> 00:03:09.440
 but for me, I pretty much just make users and call it good.

00:03:09.440 --> 00:03:12.060
 Later, we're going to learn how to use social login,

00:03:12.060 --> 00:03:14.180
 so we'll use GitHub to log people in,

00:03:14.180 --> 00:03:15.900
 so you don't have to create any users

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:18.380
 other than your admin user, but in the short term,

00:03:18.380 --> 00:03:20.820
 we're just going to use what are called local users,

00:03:20.820 --> 00:03:23.500
 which are stuck in a database, kept in the database,

00:03:23.500 --> 00:03:25.780
 and easy to create, easy to maintain,

00:03:25.780 --> 00:03:28.740
 but you tend to have to manually maintain them a little bit.

00:03:28.740 --> 00:03:29.780
 So next, we're going to look at,

00:03:29.780 --> 00:03:31.340
 now that you've got a user,

00:03:31.340 --> 00:03:35.120
 how do we, in our application code, log in and log out users.

00:03:35.120 --> 00:03:37.700
 (upbeat music)

